  },
  {
    "type": "image",
    "img_path": "output/Truly Scale-Equivariant Deep Nets with Fourier Layers_poster/visuals/images/fig_1.jpg",
    "image_caption": [
      "Scale Equivariance: "
    ],
    "image_footnote": [],
    "bbox": [
      15,
      222,
      233,
      367
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "list",
    "sub_type": "text",
    "list_items": [
      "·Scale-equivariance is crucial for consistent performance ",
      "·Prior works did not consider aliasing,resulting in equivariance error "
    ],
    "bbox": [
      21,
      388,
      244,
      450
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Can we design a perfect scale equivariant layer? ",
    "bbox": [
      7,
      461,
      187,
      481
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "·Maintain scale consistency while achieving good performance ",
    "bbox": [
      21,
      483,
      244,
      503
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Contributions: ",
    "text_level": 1,
    "bbox": [
      7,
      508,
      64,
      525
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "list",
    "sub_type": "text",
    "list_items": [
      "·Propose scale-equivariant Fourier Layer ",
      "·End-to-end equivariance with non-linearity and pooling ",
      "· Connect scale equivariance to classification task for improved scale consistency. "
    ],
    "bbox": [
      21,
      529,
      244,
      616
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "INTRODUCTION ",
    "text_level": 1,
    "bbox": [
      6,
      645,
      92,
      665
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Scaling Operation: Down-scaling a signal x ∈ RNcan be performed by subsampling by a scaling factor, i.e., ",
    "bbox": [
      6,
      679,
      244,
      722
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\n\\operatorname {S u b} _ {R} (\\mathbf {x}) [ n ] = \\mathbf {x} [ R n ].\n$$",
    "text_format": "latex",
    "bbox": [
      85,
      732,
      164,
      754
    ],
    "page_idx": 0,
    "img_path": ""
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Ideal Down-sampling: To avoid aliasing from subsampling,a lowpass filter $h$ must be performed,i.e., ",
    "bbox": [
      6,
      764,
      244,
      806
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\n\\mathcal {D} _ {R} (\\mathbf {x}) = \\operatorname {S u b} _ {R} (\\mathbf {h} * \\mathbf {x}).\n$$",
    "text_format": "latex",
    "bbox": [
      81,
      815,
      169,
      839
    ],
    "page_idx": 0,
    "img_path": ""
  },
  {
    "type": "image",
    "img_path": "output/Truly Scale-Equivariant Deep Nets with Fourier Layers_poster/visuals/images/fig_2.jpg",
    "image_caption": [],
    "image_footnote": [],
    "bbox": [
      13,
      853,
      236,
      979
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "OUR APPROACH",
    "text_level": 1,
    "bbox": [
      256,
      166,
      344,
      189
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Scale Equivariant Deep Nets ",
    "text_level": 1,
    "bbox": [
      268,
      206,
      375,
      227
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "Let $g$ denote a deep net such that $\\mathbf { y } = g ( \\mathbf { x } )$ . If this deep net $g$ can be equivalently represented as a set of functions $\\dot { \\tilde { G } } _ { k } : \\mathbb { C } ^ { 2 k + 1 }  \\dot { \\mathbb { C } }$ such that ",
    "bbox": [
      267,
      235,
      604,
      276
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "equation",
    "text": "$$\n\\mathbf {Y} [ k ] = \\tilde {G} _ {k} (\\mathbf {X} [ - k: k ]) \\forall k\n$$",
    "text_format": "latex",
    "bbox": [
      386,
      292,
      486,
      318
    ],
    "page_idx": 0,
    "img_path": ""
  },
  {
    "type": "text",
    "text": "then $g$ is scale-equivariant. In other words, the output’s frequency terms can only depend on the terms in X that are equal or lower in frequencies. We illustrate this structure with a linear function, $\\tilde { G }$ , in the Figure. The values of the Grey cells are 0. ",
    "bbox": [
      267,
      334,
      605,
      399
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "image",
    "img_path": "output/Truly Scale-Equivariant Deep Nets with Fourier Layers_poster/visuals/images/fig_3.jpg",
    "image_caption": [],
    "image_footnote": [],
    "bbox": [
      270,
      424,
      403,
      601
    ],
    "page_idx": 0
  },
  {
    "type": "image",
    "img_path": "output/Truly Scale-Equivariant Deep Nets with Fourier Layers_poster/visuals/images/fig_4.jpg",
    "image_caption": [],
    "image_footnote": [],
    "bbox": [
